## Business Logic

### 1. Summary of the Account Management Service

The Account Management Service is designed to facilitate comprehensive account operations, including the creation, retrieval, updating, and deletion of user accounts. The service ensures account integrity by implementing validation checks on account attributes and preventing duplicate account creation. It interacts with external services for account validation and manages data persistence across multiple database systems. The service employs a messaging system to publish events related to account changes, ensuring effective communication for further processing or notifications. Key stakeholders include end users, account service operators, database administrators, and external validation services, all of whom play a critical role in the service's operation.

### 2. Breakdown Table

| Base Path                | Source Repository                      | Description                                                                                               |
|--------------------------|----------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| `/accounts`              | [GitHub Repo Link](#) (Update with actual repository link) | API for managing user accounts, allowing operations such as creation, retrieval, updating, and deletion.   |

### 3. Overall API Specification

| Endpoint          | Method | Description                       | Request Body      | Response Status | Response Body               |
|-------------------|--------|-----------------------------------|--------------------|------------------|------------------------------|
| /accounts         | GET    | Retrieve all accounts             | -                  | 200              | List of Account objects     |
| /accounts         | POST   | Create a new account              | Account object      | 201              | Created Account object      |
| /accounts/{id}    | GET    | Retrieve account by ID            | -                  | 200              | Account object              |
|                   |        |                                   | -                  | 404              | Not Found                   |
| /accounts/{id}    | PUT    | Update an existing account        | Account object      | 200              | Updated Account object      |
|                   |        |                                   | -                  | 404              | Not Found                   |
| /accounts/{id}    | DELETE | Delete an account                 | -                  | 204              | No Content                  |
|                   |        |                                   | -                  | 404              | Not Found                   |

### 4. Endpoints

- **GET /accounts**: Retrieve a list of all accounts.
- **POST /accounts**: Create a new account.
- **GET /accounts/{id}**: Retrieve a specific account by ID.
- **PUT /accounts/{id}**: Update an existing account by ID.
- **DELETE /accounts/{id}**: Delete an account by ID. 

This structured approach outlines the core functionality, interactions, and expected behaviors of the Account Management Service, ensuring clarity for stakeholders and developers alike.

## Plant UML script

Here is the PlantUML sequence diagram script based on the provided business logic:

```plantuml
@startuml

actor EndUser as User
participant "AccountController" as Controller
participant "AccountService" as Service
participant "AccountRepository\n(PostgreSQL)" as AccountRepo
participant "BankRepository\n(MongoDB)" as BankRepo
participant "account-validation-service" as ExternalService
participant "KafkaMessagePublisher" as KafkaPublisher
participant "RabbitMQPublisher" as RabbitMQPublisher

== Retrieve All Accounts ==
User -> Controller : GET /accounts
Controller -> Service : retrieveAllAccounts()
Service -> AccountRepo : findAll()
AccountRepo -> Service : List<Account>
Service -> Controller : List<Account>
Controller -> User : 200 OK, List of Accounts

== Create Account ==
User -> Controller : POST /accounts\n(Account Object)
Controller -> Service : createAccount(Account)
Service -> AccountRepo : checkDuplicate(Account.id)
AccountRepo -> Service : AccountExists?
alt Account Exists
    Service -> Controller : 409 Conflict
    Controller -> User : 409 Conflict, "Account already exists"
else Account Does Not Exist
    Service -> BankRepo : createBankEntity(Account)
    BankRepo -> Service : BankEntity
    Service -> AccountRepo : save(Account)
    AccountRepo -> Service : Saved Account
    Service -> RabbitMQPublisher : publishAccountCreation(Account)
    RabbitMQPublisher -> Service : Message Published
    Service -> KafkaPublisher : publishAccountUpdate(Account)
    KafkaPublisher -> Service : Message Published
    Service -> Controller : 201 Created, Account
    Controller -> User : 201 Created, Account
end

== Retrieve Account by ID ==
User -> Controller : GET /accounts/{id}
Controller -> Service : retrieveAccountById(id)
Service -> AccountRepo : findById(id)
AccountRepo -> Service : Account or null
alt Account Found
    Service -> Controller : Account
    Controller -> User : 200 OK, Account
else Account Not Found
    Service -> Controller : 404 Not Found
    Controller -> User : 404 Not Found
end

== Update Account ==
User -> Controller : PUT /accounts/{id}\n(Account Object)
Controller -> Service : updateAccount(id, Account)
Service -> AccountRepo : findById(id)
AccountRepo -> Service : Account or null
alt Account Found
    Service -> AccountRepo : update(Account)
    AccountRepo -> Service : Updated Account
    Service -> KafkaPublisher : publishAccountUpdate(Account)
    KafkaPublisher -> Service : Message Published
    Service -> Controller : 200 OK, Updated Account
    Controller -> User : 200 OK, Updated Account
else Account Not Found
    Service -> Controller : 404 Not Found
    Controller -> User : 404 Not Found
end

== Delete Account ==
User -> Controller : DELETE /accounts/{id}
Controller -> Service : deleteAccount(id)
Service -> AccountRepo : findById(id)
AccountRepo -> Service : Account or null
alt Account Found
    Service -> AccountRepo : delete(id)
    AccountRepo -> Service : Deleted
    Service -> RabbitMQPublisher : publishAccountDeletion(id)
    RabbitMQPublisher -> Service : Message Published
    Service -> Controller : 204 No Content
    Controller -> User : 204 No Content
else Account Not Found
    Service -> Controller : 404 Not Found
    Controller -> User : 404 Not Found
end

@enduml
```

### Explanation:
- **Actors and Participants**: The diagram includes all key actors (End User, AccountController, AccountService, etc.) and their interactions.
- **Main Interactions**: Each endpoint is represented with the corresponding interactions and messages exchanged between the components.
- **Decision Points**: The diagram highlights critical decision points, such as checking for duplicate accounts, finding accounts, and handling errors.
- **Messaging**: It shows the publishing of messages to RabbitMQ and Kafka based on the business logic specified.
- **Endpoints**: All specified API endpoints are covered in the interactions. 

This script can be used directly in a PlantUML environment to generate the corresponding sequence diagram.

# API Documentation

## /accounts GET
Endpoint URL: /accounts  
HTTP Method: GET  
Authentication: None  
Authorization: None  
Description: Retrieve all accounts.  

### Request Parameters
| Parameter Name | Type   | Required | Description                |
|----------------|--------|----------|----------------------------|
| None           | -      | No       | No request parameters needed|

### Sample Request
```json
{}
```

### Response Parameters
| Field Name      | Type   | Description                  |
|------------------|--------|------------------------------|
| accounts         | array  | List of Account objects      |

### Sample Response
```json
{
  "accounts": [
    {
      "id": "1",
      "name": "John Doe",
      "email": "john.doe@example.com",
      "accountNumber": "123456789",
      "accountType": "savings",
      "dob": "1990-01-01",
      "bankCode": "XYZ123"
    }
  ]
}
```

### Components Involved
- AccountController
- AccountService
- AccountRepository (PostgreSQL)

### Data Mapping
| Source Field     | Target Field           | Transformation               |
|------------------|------------------------|-------------------------------|
| None             | accounts               | Direct retrieval from DB      |

### Sample Errors
```json
{
  "error": "No accounts found",
  "code": 404,
  "message": "No accounts exist in the database."
}
```

### Root Exception Details
| Name                     | Description                          | Header/Payload | Type   | Mandatory/Optional | Notes             |
|--------------------------|--------------------------------------|----------------|--------|--------------------|-------------------|
| ResourceNotFoundException | Thrown when no accounts are found    | -              | -      | Mandatory           | Indicates absence of data |

### Error Codes
| HTTP Code | Message                | Description                     |
|-----------|------------------------|---------------------------------|
| 404       | Not Found              | No accounts exist in the database. |

## /accounts POST
Endpoint URL: /accounts  
HTTP Method: POST  
Authentication: None  
Authorization: None  
Description: Create a new account.  

### Request Parameters
| Parameter Name | Type   | Required | Description                          |
|----------------|--------|----------|--------------------------------------|
| account        | object | Yes      | Account object containing account details. |

### Sample Request
```json
{
  "name": "John Doe",
  "email": "john.doe@example.com",
  "accountNumber": "123456789",
  "accountType": "savings",
  "dob": "1990-01-01",
  "bankCode": "XYZ123"
}
```

### Response Parameters
| Field Name      | Type   | Description                      |
|------------------|--------|----------------------------------|
| id               | string | Unique identifier for the account |
| name             | string | Name of the account holder       |
| email            | string | Email address of the account holder |
| accountNumber    | string | Account number                   |
| accountType      | string | Type of account                  |
| dob              | string | Date of birth of the account holder |
| bankCode         | string | Bank code associated with the account |

### Sample Response
```json
{
  "id": "1",
  "name": "John Doe",
  "email": "john.doe@example.com",
  "accountNumber": "123456789",
  "accountType": "savings",
  "dob": "1990-01-01",
  "bankCode": "XYZ123"
}
```

### Components Involved
- AccountController
- AccountService
- AccountRepository (PostgreSQL)
- RabbitMQPublisher

### Data Mapping
| Source Field     | Target Field           | Transformation               |
|------------------|------------------------|-------------------------------|
| account.name     | AccountEntity.name     | Direct mapping                |
| account.email    | AccountEntity.email    | Direct mapping                |
| account.accountNumber | AccountEntity.accountNumber | Direct mapping         |
| account.accountType | AccountEntity.accountType | Direct mapping            |
| account.dob      | AccountEntity.dob      | Direct mapping                |
| account.bankCode  | AccountEntity.bankCode | Direct mapping                |

### Sample Errors
```json
{
  "error": "Account already exists",
  "code": 409,
  "message": "An account with this ID already exists."
}
```

### Root Exception Details
| Name                     | Description                          | Header/Payload | Type   | Mandatory/Optional | Notes             |
|--------------------------|--------------------------------------|----------------|--------|--------------------|-------------------|
| DuplicateAccountException | Thrown when trying to create a duplicate account | -              | -      | Mandatory           | Indicates duplicate entry |

### Error Codes
| HTTP Code | Message                | Description                     |
|-----------|------------------------|---------------------------------|
| 409       | Conflict               | An account with this ID already exists. |
